				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I think at least one part of the reason for the restriction is when you're actually modulating content for OTA broadcast — i.e. not just over the little yellow composite cable — the broadcaster has to both 1- send a signal that complies with what the FCC says is ok and 2- deal with the AGC on the input to each television.
<br />1- I'm not certain how this would affect IRE levels; AFAICT, as long as the negative edge is above -40 IRE (sync) it should be ok.
<br />2- Because NTSC OTA is AM modualted, each television has to have an AGC to scale the input to the nominal levels. Since this scaling happens before colorspace conversion, it's possible this stage will distort all the colors towards desaturated black or oversaturated white if a hot color is present.
<br />
<br />And as a final anecdote, <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.linusakesson.net/scene/phasor/">http://www.linusakesson.net/scene/phasor/</a><!-- m --> did explicitly have problems with hot colors in his video generation (although his is PAL hot colors instead of NTSC).</div>

